    "NameOfTraveler":"Ruy Gonzalez de Clavijo",
    "YearOfTravel":1404,
    "Description":"On Tuesday, the 12th of August, they dined and took their siesta on a great plain, where there was a large building, and men watching the horses of the lord ; and they mounted, and rode away from that place, at the hour of vespers.\n\nAt the hour of vespers they departed, and reached a city called Anchoy, of which one of the attendants of the ambassadors was a native. This city was beyond the land of Media, in a land called Tagiguinia, and the language of the people differed from the Persian. The men of the city received the ambassadors with much honour, and they remained there until Thursday, the 14th of August. They were well supplied with plenty of meat and wine ; and were presented with a robe, and a horse. This city is in a plain, and is surrounded, for two leagues, by many gardens, vineyards, and houses, with numerous channels of water.",
    "Citation":"Clavijo, Ruy Gonzalez de. Narrative of the Embassy of Ruy Gonzalez De Clavijo to the Court of Timour, at Samarcand, A.d. 1403-6. Translated by CLements R. Markham. London: Printed for the Hakluyt Society, 1847. https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/000059571.",
